URN:CornellLabOfOrnithology:EBIRD:OBS259687492	2021-03-19 08:42:34.111265	32181	species	Henslow's Sparrow	Centronyx henslowii			2	A 	C3	A 	Female, Adult (1); Male, Adult (1)	United States	US	Michigan	US-MI	Allegan	US-MI-005	US-MI_1590	23			Allegan SGA--Grasslands at 117th and 58th	L2919688	P	42.5410343	-86.1082864	2014-06-14	09:49:00	obsr228203	S18785939	Traveling	P22	EBIRD	91	1.609		3	1		0	1	0		At first with Rick Brigham, then joined by Tom Beeke and briefly by Bob ?	Singing male perched on rightmost of two very short cedars at 42.540951, -86.107192.  Perhaps scopable from the road with minimal heat distortion, but if singing easily heard.  Carefully followed a mowed trail into the field (there are no signs prohibiting public entry anywhere) and got stellar looks at the singing male in this cedar.  Then the male went down for a while and never perched in clear sight again.  A female came up and began chirping while the male did circles around us in the grass (out of sight) while singing, so at that point we conscientiously left the area. The pair appears to be defending a nest site just west of these two short cedar trees in the lush grass near the mowed trail.  Our encounter was incidental and unexpected, but please keep a distance if chasing these birds to help keep them happily breeding in the area.

Singing softly in the field directly behind the parking area which has very good habitat with old dry matted vegetation among the grasses and weeds. I remember visiting this location many years ago during the cerulean warbler festival as Greg Nelson lead our group in search of the Henslow’s Sparrow but without success. URN:CornellLabOfOrnithology:EBIRD:OBS512610442	2017-06-20 13:55:07	32181	species	Henslow's Sparrow	Centronyx henslowii			1					United States	US	Michigan	US-MI	Benzie	US-MI-019	US-MI_2900	12			Sleeping Bear Dunes NL--Esch Rd. at M-22	L1672911	H	44.7620602	-86.0491779	2017-06-20	08:55:00	obsr280244	S37701408	Stationary	P21	EBIRD	30			1	1		1	1	1		Joined Carl Freeman and 2 other birders on the east side of M-22, between Esch and Aral Roads.	Continuing bird.  The sparrow was perched and singing on top of some vetch, approx. 85-90 yards --away, when I arrived.  The song was audible and quite distinctive;   "tsi-lick" or "flee-sic, " just as described in various references.  The view of the bird through binoculars was decent, but the dense vegetation, often swaying in the wind, made it a little difficult to get an unobstructed photo.  I saw the bird take flight twice:  the flights were short, weak and low, with the bird going from the top of one plant  to another.  Diagnostic marks:  Small sparrow with large bill, flat head and notched tail.  Olive tint to the face and head, with malar and other dark stripping.  Crown with brown & tan stripes.  White throat and belly. Streaks on breast. Reddish scapulars.  Photos.

Gentle wind, 72F	In prairie, just south of the interpretive signage. First ID’d by its song, an unmistakeable short, crisp chureep. Then we spotted in on a low stem. It sang steadily for the 10 minutes we watched it. Small sparrow with large head and large finch-like beak. Soft yellowish face and slightly brighter yellow patch just above eye. Dark strip down center of crown, one dark streak trailing back from eye, one from beak, and one steak down each side of throat. Clean white throat with a bib of soft streaks high on chest and down the flanks. Buffy white belly. Will attach photos when able to access my computer tomorrow.

Joined in calling by another bird to the east (which I never saw) about 20 minutes into viewing period.  --First bird stayed south or south-east of the mowed area the whole time, popping up on old mullein stems a few times, but mostly staying down mid-level in grasses, or disappearing completely into the lower parts of prairie.  Calls a sharp "Tsee-thlek". Sounded deceptively close, usually found bird calling about twice as far away as I'd estimated from the sound. Head flattish. Auricular and upper chest striping seen well, head was slightly greenish, cheeks dark, chin white/light.  Bold dark double head stripe. Wings had nice blocks of rich red-brown colour.  Tail short. Have observed a couple of times in Canada (Ontario), but first for me in USA.

Stayed concealed in grasses and never would give me a visual even though it was within 40 feet from me at various times.. Identical short cadenced song as represented in Sibley App (songs #1_NY; and songs #2_NY) but pitch seemed to be intermediate between them. Located in field on east side of road exactly 2.3 miles north of the intersection of Riverside Dr. and Jackson Road. There is a parking  area on the east side of the road - identified by distinct signage for horse rider and dog (picture) and an instructional sign reading "Hunters: Dog field trials may be in progress. Keep a safe..." The correct location is also identifiable by a group of about six large rocks in front of a small silver swing gate near the signs. Birds were easily heard from the parking lot/gate - which is how I serendipitously found them (turning around due to inaccurate directions).

L1742407	P	42.4071750	-85.3473322	2016-04-30	18:00:00	obsr101812	S36445842	Traveling	P22	EBIRD	35	0.483		1	1		0	1	0			Yard lifer.  This bird was first heard on 4/28/16, at night. On the date of this checklist, 4/30/16,  I actually had a good view of it through binoculars.  This was the only time I was able to get a good view of it, and I was unable to get any pictures, but I have several recordings of its very recognizable song that I would  be happy to submit if necessary. Most of these were recorded at night--this was also the first time I learned that Henslow's were known to call at night. ----The bird was first heard for 14 consecutive days, 4/28/16 - 5/11/16.  It was not heard again until 5/15/16*, then on 5/16, 5/17, 5/19, and 5/20.  (* My notes read, "Interim between 5/11 and 5/15 unseasonably cold.")  Overall I heard it on our property on most of the 23 days between 4/28 and 5/20.  Then it seemed to disappear, but on 5/28, 5/29, and 5/31  I heard it (or another conspecific, but that seems unlikely) calling, also at night, from across the street, seeming to come from the field near the south end of my neighbors' driveway.----I speculated that this might be a first year breeding male trying to attract a female but without success; at least I never saw or heard any evidence of another conspecific. I'm very eager to see if it returns this year.----I realize these notes are not organized to fit eBird's data protocols...I enter them here mostly for my own records.  The bird was heard primarily when I took my dogs out at night, but also occasionally during daylight hours as well.  It seemed to have a territory just behind the row of blue spruces that separate the lawn from the old field, in the shrubby growth that's infiltrating the field. On a few occasions when my adult daughter was home she also heard it.

Bird or birds reported previously.  A birder we met on arrival to the old model airplane field --had walked east near some irrigation equipment and located a singing bird.  We found a different bird west of the model airplane driveway and 150 yards east of a north-south tree line.  Slow, persistent walking and driving paid off for us after one and a half hours.  We identified the bird first by song and saw it later as it perched on some vegetation 35 yards away.   Small sparrow with large heavy bill and flat-headed look.  Dark brown primaries, rusty brown/chestnut on secondaries, olive color on head; thin, dark streaks on breast, throat pale, flesh-colored legs.  Overall darker appearance than the nearby Grasshopper Sparrows.  Photos were taken, but most were not in focus due to the thick vegetation between us and the bird.

URN:CornellLabOfOrnithology:EBIRD:OBS407215191	2016-06-19 16:49:17	32181	species	Henslow's Sparrow	Centronyx henslowii			2					United States	US	Michigan	US-MI	Saginaw	US-MI-145	US-MI_1644	12	USFWS_750		Shiawassee NWR - Little Prairie Units	L1738920	P	43.3247250	-84.0394591	2016-05-25	08:30:00	obsr147420	S29908753	Stationary	P21	EBIRD	20			1	0		0	1	1			Both ID by tsillik song. The birds were close to each other, so time and care were taken to be certain that two birds were present, not just one sounding like two as a result of singing while facing towards and then away from the listener. One individual also ID'd by sight, as it sang from a weed stem. No views of back, all of front. Small, compact sparrow with a relatively large, very light tan/pink colored bill, and slightly darker pink/tan legs and feet. White belly and throat, separated by an only slightly buffy breast band. Breast band had little if any fine dark streaks, but dark streaks were present on sides of buffy breast and flanks (although not near as conspicuous, as on, say, a Savannah Sparrow). Sides of head were buffy colored with dark lateral crown stripes bordering buffy median stripe. Buffy richest in color on supraloral. Dark eye line posterior of light ringed eye was large and obvious, more so than mustache and lateral throat stripes. First time for this observer finding this species in this meadow. Another NWR meadow several miles to the north, that this species had occupied for the last two years, underwent a prescribed fire this spring, so the potential exists that the little colony relocated to the nearest suitable NWR location.

URN:CornellLabOfOrnithology:EBIRD:OBS566117429	2018-01-10 17:43:22	32181	species	Henslow's Sparrow	Centronyx henslowii			2					United States	US	Michigan	US-MI	Wayne	US-MI-163		23			Oakwoods Metropark	L139837	H	42.1063004	-83.3179016	2005-06-24	09:30:00	obsr218010	S41803217	Traveling	P22	EBIRD	120	4.828		2	0		0	1	0		Walt Pawlowski standing near location where Henslow's Sparrow found.	As I arrived, I saw Walt Pawlowski standing near the area where the Henslow's were being heard.  We were able to confirm at least 2 individuals very near to where we were standing.  I took a GPS reading for records sake:----N42º06.417'--W083º21.013'----Savannah Sparrows were also being heard, but the distinctive 'tslik' of the Henslows was unmistakable.  I took several photos of the grassland habitat, which consisted mainly of tall grasses with a few thistle.  After Walt left the area, I found a spot a few feet west of the location where a single Bull Thistle stood adjacent to a small depression in the grass.  A single Henslow's was singing from what appeared to be the shallow depression area.  I did not approach the area for fear of disturbing a possible nest.

URN:CornellLabOfOrnithology:EBIRD:OBS493431197	2017-05-07 23:26:05	32181	species	Henslow's Sparrow	Centronyx henslowii			3					United States	US	Michigan	US-MI	Wayne	US-MI-163		23			Willow Run Airport (restricted access)	L426624	H	42.2326880	-83.5077989	2007-06-06		obsr130801	S36483503	Historical	P62	EBIRD				2	0		0	1	0		birding with Allen Chartier. Reconstructed from old post to Mich-listers: "Yesterday morning (June 6), Neil Gilbert and I set out for birding sites in western Washtenaw County. First, we stopped at Willow Run Airport (Wayne Co.) where we found three singing HENSLOW'S SPARROWS. The birds were at the east end of the airport. On the map in A Birder's Guide to Michigan (page 84), this is south of Tyler Road, on the east side of the north-south road around the airport. There were also Bobolinks in this field, and at least 8 Grasshopper Sparrows at various other places around the airport. A single Western Meadowlark was singing a great distance away, in the middle of the runways, as is often the case here. (Western Meadowlarks arrived here on April 19.)"
